def: An ecclesiastical who holds but one benefice; -- distinguishedfrom pluralist. [Eng.] V. Knox.
Capable of being pictured, or represented by a picture.
A boat used in fishing with trawls or trawlnets.
Frequenting playhouses; as, the playgoing public.-- n.
A spectroscope arranged for attachment to a microscope, forobservation of the spectrum of light from minute portions of anysubstance.
One of a coterie who exclude others; one who from real ofaffected fastidiousness limits his acquaintance to a select few.
One who equivocates.Here's an equivocator that could swear in both the scales againsteither scale, yet could not equivocate to heaven. Shak.
To jape; to laugh at; to deceive. [Obs.] Chaucer.
One who instructs in the art of improving or using the memory.
A basket made of rushes, used chiefly for containing figs andraisins.
To banish; to drive out; to expel. [Obs.] "Appetite flemethdiscretion." Chaucer.
